# CodeWeave: Comprehensive Learning & Interview Guide

> [!NOTE]
> This is a living document. Updated after every major phase of development. Use this to confidently explain every architectural decision in an interview setting.

---

## 🗺️ TECH STACK OVERVIEW

| Layer | Technology | Why |
|---|---|---|
| **Frontend** | React + Vite | Fast HMR dev server, component-based UI |
| **Editor** | Monaco Editor (`@monaco-editor/react`) | Same engine as VS Code — syntax highlighting, full IDE UX |
| **Real-time sync** | Yjs + y-socket.io | CRDT-based peer-to-peer conflict resolution |
| **Backend** | Node.js + Express | Non-blocking I/O, ideal for WebSocket-heavy apps |
| **WebSockets** | Socket.io | Reliable duplex communication with auto-reconnect |
| **Database** | MongoDB + Mongoose | Flexible schema for document-style workspace storage |
| **Auth** | Clerk | Enterprise-grade Identity Provider; removes auth liability |
| **Code Execution** | Judge0 CE Cloud API | Sandboxed multi-language execution; no server infra needed |
| **Architecture** | MVC (Model-View-Controller) | Industry-standard separation of concerns |

---

## 🟢 PHASE 1 & 2: Dynamic Routing & Collaboration Experience

To confidently defend the real-time collaboration features, master three core concepts: **Dynamic Routing**, **CRDTs (Yjs)**, and **The Awareness Protocol**.

### Concept 1: Dynamic Routing (React Router)

**The Problem:** The original app connected all users to a single global room because the backend and frontend had no way to differentiate sessions.

**The Solution:** React Router maps distinct URLs to different workspaces.

```jsx
// Room.jsx
const { roomId } = useParams() // Extracts ID from /room/:id
const provider = new SocketIOProvider("http://localhost:3000", roomId, ydoc)
// roomId becomes the y-socket.io document namespace — auto-isolates the room
```

**How it works:** `useParams()` extracts the dynamic segment from the URL (e.g., `/room/abc123`). That `roomId` is passed as the document name into `SocketIOProvider`. The backend automatically isolates broadcasting to only the users connected to that exact document name — no backend room management code required.

> **Interview Q:** *"How did you handle multiple separate workspaces simultaneously?"*
>
> **Your Answer:** *"I used React Router to create dynamic URL parameters (`/room/:id`). On the client, I extract that ID with `useParams()` and use it as the y-socket.io document namespace. The backend automatically isolates real-time broadcasting to only users sharing that URL — without needing any custom backend room management logic."*

---

### Concept 2: CRDTs and Yjs (The Brain of the Editor)

**The Problem:** If two users edit the exact same character position simultaneously, how do you prevent data loss or document corruption?

**The Solution:** **Conflict-free Replicated Data Types (CRDTs)** via Yjs.

```jsx
// Room.jsx — The three core Yjs primitives
const ydoc = useMemo(() => new Y.Doc(), [])         // The shared document
const yText = useMemo(() => ydoc.getText("monaco"), [ydoc]) // The shared text type

// MonacoBinding bridges Monaco's internal model with the Yjs CRDT
new MonacoBinding(yText, editorRef.current.getModel(), new Set([editorRef.current]), provider.awareness)
```

**How it works:** Yjs doesn't send raw strings — it tracks every **character insertion and deletion as an immutable, uniquely-timestamped operation**. When two users type at the same position, Yjs's mathematical algorithms merge both operations deterministically. The result is identical on every client, regardless of which update arrived first or network latency.

**Key insight:** This is fundamentally different from **Operational Transformation (OT)** used by Google Docs. OT requires a central server to sequence and transform operations. CRDTs resolve conflicts peer-to-peer, making the system more resilient and horizontally scalable.

> **Interview Q:** *"How did you prevent race conditions and merge conflicts when multiple users type simultaneously?"*
>
> **Your Answer:** *"I implemented a CRDT architecture using Yjs. Unlike Operational Transformation — which requires a central server to serialize and transform every operation — CRDTs treat each keystroke as an immutable, uniquely-identified state update. Yjs mathematically guarantees that all clients eventually converge to the exact same document state, regardless of network latency or the order updates are received."*

---

### Concept 3: The Awareness Protocol (Cursors & Presence)

**The Problem:** We need to broadcast real-time cursor positions and usernames, but we *don't* want to store mouse coordinates permanently in the CRDT document.

**The Solution:** The **Yjs Awareness Protocol** — a separate ephemeral (non-persisted) pub/sub layer.

```jsx
// Room.jsx — Injecting ephemeral presence metadata
provider.awareness.setLocalStateField("user", {
  name: username,      // Used by MonacoBinding to render cursor tooltip
  username: username,  // Used by our sidebar collaborator list
  color: userColor     // Unique hex color per session
})

// Listening to changes for the sidebar
provider.awareness.on("change", () => {
  const states = Array.from(provider.awareness.getStates().values())
  setUsers(states.filter(s => s.user).map(s => s.user))
})
```

**How it works:** Awareness data is **broadcast to all peers but never written to the CRDT document**. When a user disconnects, their awareness state is automatically garbage-collected. `MonacoBinding` reads the `name` and `color` fields from awareness to render colored cursor decorations and tooltips natively inside Monaco.

> **Interview Q:** *"How did you implement real-time remote cursors?"*
>
> **Your Answer:** *"I used the Yjs Awareness protocol. The actual code changes are synced via CRDTs for permanent persistence, but cursor positions and user presence are ephemeral — they shouldn't persist after a user leaves. I injected user metadata (name, color) into the Awareness state, which the MonacoBinding library continuously polls to render live cursor decorations. When a user disconnects, their cursor is automatically removed."*

---

## 🟢 PHASE 3: Persistent Workspaces (MongoDB)

### Concept 4: Server-Side Persistence & Lifecycle Hooks

**The Problem:** Frontend clients sending `fetch()` to save their code leads to race conditions, redundant writes, and stale data when multiple users are editing simultaneously.

**The Solution:** Making the **Node.js server the single source of truth** by hooking into `y-socket.io` lifecycle events.

```js
// yjs.socket.js — Server intercepts the Yjs document lifecycle
ysocketio.on("document-loaded", async (doc) => {
  const workspace = await Workspace.findOne({ roomId: doc.name })
  if (workspace?.content) {
    // Server overwrites whatever the client prematurely initialized
    doc.getText("monaco").insert(0, workspace.content)
  }
})

ysocketio.on("document-update", (doc) => {
  // Debounced — only writes after 2s of inactivity
  debouncedSave(doc.name, doc.getText("monaco").toString())
})
```

> **Interview Q:** *"How did you persist the real-time document state to your database?"*
>
> **Your Answer:** *"Instead of relying on the client to send HTTP requests, I built a completely server-driven persistence layer. I hooked into the y-socket.io lifecycle events — `document-loaded` fetches the last-saved state from MongoDB and injects it into the CRDT, and `document-update` triggers a debounced save. This keeps the frontend completely thin and guarantees the database always holds the authoritative, conflict-free document state."*

---

### Concept 5: Debouncing Database Writes

**The Problem:** 5 users typing at 80 WPM generates hundreds of `document-update` events per second. Writing to MongoDB on every event would instantly overwhelm the database.

**The Solution:** A server-side **debounce timer** — only commit after a period of inactivity.

```js
// In-memory map of debounce timers per room
const saveTimers = {}

const debouncedSave = (roomId, content) => {
  clearTimeout(saveTimers[roomId])
  saveTimers[roomId] = setTimeout(async () => {
    await Workspace.findOneAndUpdate({ roomId }, { content }, { upsert: true })
    console.log(`[DB] Saved room: ${roomId}`)
  }, 2000) // 2 seconds of inactivity before committing
}
```

**The result:** Instead of potentially thousands of writes per minute, you get at most **one write per 2-second idle window** — a reduction of **over 99%** in database operations.

> **Interview Q:** *"How did you prevent your database from being overwhelmed by high-frequency real-time edits?"*
>
> **Your Answer:** *"I implemented a server-side debounce mechanism. The `document-update` event fires on every CRDT operation, but instead of writing to MongoDB immediately, I store a `setTimeout` reference per room in memory. Every new update resets that timer. The actual database write only executes after 2 full seconds of inactivity. This reduces database writes by over 99% while still guaranteeing data safety."*

---

### Concept 6: Distributed System Race Conditions

**The Problem:** The React client mounts Monaco with a default `"// Start coding..."` placeholder. If the client syncs this placeholder into the CRDT *before* the server finishes querying MongoDB, the real saved code gets ignored or overwritten.

**The Solution:** **Authoritative Server Override** — the server's database read always wins.

**How it works:** In the `document-loaded` hook, once the server retrieves the stored content, it calls `doc.transact()` to atomically clear the CRDT and insert the authoritative database content. Any placeholder the client injected is wiped out.

> **Interview Q:** *"Did you encounter any race conditions in the project?"*
>
> **Your Answer:** *"Yes — WebSockets connect faster than MongoDB can query, so the CRDT would sometimes get initialized with the editor's default placeholder text before the server finished loading the real content. I solved this with an authoritative server override pattern: the `document-loaded` hook uses a transactional CRDT update to forcefully clear any prematurely injected client content and replace it with the database state. The server is the absolute source of truth."*

---

## 🟢 PHASE 4: Code Execution Engine (Judge0 CE)

This was the most systems-intensive phase, involving diagnosing a deep infrastructure incompatibility and engineering a production-grade workaround.

### Concept 9: Sandboxed Multi-Language Code Execution

**The Problem:** Executing user-submitted code on a server is extremely dangerous. Malicious code could read files, make network requests, or crash the process. You need a sandboxed execution environment.

**The Solution:** **Judge0 CE** — an open-source, sandboxed code execution system. We call its cloud-hosted API instead of running it ourselves.

**Architecture:**
```
[React Client]
     │
     │  POST /api/execution/run
     │  { sourceCode, languageId, stdin }
     ▼
[Express Server] ── execution.controller.js
     │
     │  judge0.service.js
     │  POST https://ce.judge0.com/submissions?wait=true
     ▼
[Judge0 CE Cloud]  ← Sandboxed execution environment
     │
     │  { stdout, stderr, compile_output, status, time, memory }
     ▼
[Express Server] → [React Client] → Renders in Output panel
```

**The Judge0 flow:**
1. Source code is **Base64-encoded** before transmission (avoids JSON escaping bugs with special characters)
2. Submission is sent to Judge0 with `wait=true` — the request blocks until execution completes
3. Judge0 returns `stdout`, `stderr`, `compile_output`, execution `time`, and `memory` usage
4. The server Base64-decodes the results and returns clean JSON

```js
// judge0.service.js — The core execution bridge
export const runCodeWithJudge0 = async ({ sourceCode, languageId, stdin = "" }) => {
  const judge0Url = process.env.JUDGE0_API_URL || "https://ce.judge0.com"

  const response = await fetch(`${judge0Url}/submissions?base64_encoded=true&wait=true`, {
    method: "POST",
    headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
    body: JSON.stringify({
      source_code: encodeBase64(sourceCode),
      language_id: languageId,  // e.g., 63 = JavaScript, 71 = Python
      stdin: encodeBase64(stdin),
    }),
  })

  const result = await response.json()
  return {
    stdout: decodeBase64(result.stdout),
    stderr: decodeBase64(result.stderr),
    compileOutput: decodeBase64(result.compile_output),
    status: result.status,    // { id: 3, description: "Accepted" }
    time: result.time,        // e.g., "0.024" (seconds)
    memory: result.memory,    // e.g., 7340 (KB)
  }
}
```

**Supported languages (Judge0 CE language IDs):**
| Language | ID | Monaco Mode |
|---|---|---|
| JavaScript (Node.js 18) | 63 | `javascript` |
| Python 3 | 71 | `python` |
| C++ (GCC 10) | 54 | `cpp` |
| Java 15 | 62 | `java` |

> **Interview Q:** *"How did you implement secure, multi-language code execution?"*
>
> **Your Answer:** *"I integrated with the Judge0 CE API, an open-source sandboxed code execution system. User code is Base64-encoded on the server and submitted to Judge0's cloud instance. Judge0 runs the code inside an `isolate` sandbox — a Linux namespace that restricts filesystem, network, and process access. The API returns structured output including `stdout`, `stderr`, compile errors, execution time, and memory usage. This gives users a full IDE-like execution experience without any security risk to my server."*

---

### Concept 10: Infrastructure Debugging — cgroup v2 Incompatibility

This is a **premium interview talking point** — it demonstrates systems-level debugging skills most candidates don't have.

**The Problem:** Judge0 was deployed locally via Docker Desktop on Windows, but every code execution returned:
```
"message": "No such file or directory @ rb_sysopen - /box/script.js",
"status": { "id": 13, "description": "Internal Error" }
```

The container was running. The API was responding. The language IDs were correct. Everything *looked* fine.

**The Diagnosis (3-layer investigation):**
1. **Layer 1 — Verified connectivity:** `netstat` confirmed port 2358 was open and listening. The Docker container was definitely up.
2. **Layer 2 — Direct API test:** Hitting the local Judge0 API directly returned the "Internal Error" — eliminating the Node.js app as the source.
3. **Layer 3 — Root cause:** Judge0's `isolate` sandbox creates execution environments using **Linux cgroup v1** to enforce CPU/memory limits. Docker Desktop on Windows uses WSL2, which enforces **cgroup v2** exclusively. The two are fundamentally incompatible — `isolate` cannot find the cgroup v1 filesystem structures and fails to create the `/box` sandbox directory.

**The Fix — Cloud Migration:**
```
# Before: Broken local Docker
JUDGE0_API_URL=http://localhost:2358

# After: Free cloud CE instance (cgroup-agnostic, no setup)
JUDGE0_API_URL=https://ce.judge0.com
```

By pointing the service at the **official Judge0 CE cloud instance** (`https://ce.judge0.com`), we bypassed the entire Windows/cgroup incompatibility. The cloud instance runs on Linux with cgroup v1 and requires no API key for standard use.

**Verified fix:**
```json
// Test response after migration
{
  "stdout": "Fix confirmed!\n",
  "status": { "id": 3, "description": "Accepted" },
  "time": "0.024",
  "memory": 7340
}
```

> **Interview Q:** *"What was the hardest technical bug you solved in this project?"*
>
> **Your Answer:** *"The hardest was a deep infrastructure incompatibility. My local Judge0 Docker container was running, the port was open, but every execution returned a cryptic 'Internal Error — /box/script.js not found.' After confirming the container was healthy, I isolated the problem to Judge0's `isolate` sandbox, which creates execution environments using Linux cgroup v1 to enforce resource limits. Docker Desktop on Windows runs WSL2, which enforces cgroup v2 — a fundamentally incompatible kernel interface. `isolate` couldn't find the cgroup v1 filesystem and failed to create the execution sandbox. My solution was to migrate to the Judge0 CE cloud instance, which runs on native Linux. This eliminated the infrastructure incompatibility entirely and required only a one-line environment variable change."*

---

### Concept 11: Base64 Encoding for Code Payloads

**Why Base64-encode source code before sending to Judge0?**

Raw source code contains characters that are problematic inside JSON strings: backslashes, double quotes, newlines, and null bytes. If a Python program contains `print("hello\nworld")`, serializing it naively into JSON would break the JSON structure. Base64 encoding converts arbitrary binary/text data into a safe ASCII character set (`A-Z`, `a-z`, `0-9`, `+`, `/`), eliminating all JSON escaping issues.

```js
const encodeBase64 = (value = "") => Buffer.from(value, "utf-8").toString("base64")
const decodeBase64 = (value) => value ? Buffer.from(value, "base64").toString("utf-8") : ""
```

> **Interview Q:** *"Why did you Base64-encode the source code before sending it to Judge0?"*
>
> **Your Answer:** *"Source code can contain any character — backslashes, double quotes, control characters — all of which are semantically significant in JSON. Base64 encoding converts the raw source into a safe ASCII subset that serializes cleanly into JSON without escaping conflicts. Judge0 natively supports the `base64_encoded=true` query parameter, so it decodes the payload on its end transparently."*

---

## 🟢 ARCHITECTURE: Model-View-Controller (MVC) Pattern

### Concept 12: Separation of Concerns (MVC)

**The Problem:** Stacking all database logic, API routes, and WebSocket listeners into a single `server.js` creates unmaintainable "spaghetti code."

**The Solution:** Industry-standard **MVC (Model-View-Controller)** architecture.

```
server/src/
├── config/
│   └── db.js                     # Database connection (MongoDB/Mongoose)
├── models/
│   └── Workspace.model.js        # M — Data schema definition
├── controllers/
│   ├── workspace.controller.js   # C — Business logic (CRUD)
│   └── execution.controller.js   # C — Code execution logic
├── routes/
│   ├── workspace.routes.js       # Traffic cop — maps URLs to controllers
│   └── execution.routes.js       # POST /api/execution/run
├── services/
│   └── judge0.service.js         # External API abstraction layer
├── sockets/
│   └── yjs.socket.js             # WebSocket lifecycle handlers
└── server.js                     # Entry point — orchestrates all modules
```

**The Service Layer:** Beyond MVC, we added a `services/` directory for external API calls (Judge0). This is the **Repository/Service Pattern** — controllers never call external APIs directly. This makes services independently testable and swappable.

> **Interview Q:** *"How did you structure your backend for scalability?"*
>
> **Your Answer:** *"I adopted a strict MVC architecture with an additional Service layer for external API integrations. Models handle the Mongoose schema, Controllers contain business logic, Routes act as traffic cops mapping URLs to controllers, and Services abstract third-party API calls like Judge0. This means `server.js` is just a clean entry-point orchestrator — adding a new feature only touches the relevant layer without risking regression in others."*

---

## 🟢 NETWORKING & DEBUGGING: Overcoming Systems Failures

### Concept 13: Cross-Origin WebSocket Failures

**The Problem:** The frontend UI loaded perfectly, but real-time cursor syncing failed completely in the browser.

**The Root Cause:** Vite runs the frontend on port `5173`. The y-socket.io client was connecting to a relative path (`"/"`), which resolved to the Vite dev server — not the Express backend on port `3000`. The Vite server doesn't speak the Socket.io protocol, so the WebSocket handshake silently failed.

**The Fix:**
```jsx
// Wrong — connects to Vite dev server on port 5173
new SocketIOProvider("/", roomId, ydoc)

// Correct — explicitly targets the Express backend
new SocketIOProvider("http://localhost:3000", roomId, ydoc)
```

Plus adding `cors` middleware on Express:
```js
app.use(cors())
const io = new Server(httpServer, { cors: { origin: "*" } })
```

> **Interview Q:** *"Did you face any issues connecting your frontend to the backend?"*
>
> **Your Answer:** *"Yes — when splitting into a Vite frontend and Express backend on different ports, my WebSocket client silently connected to the wrong server because it used a relative path. I debugged this using browser DevTools Network tab, saw the socket upgrade failing on port 5173, and fixed it by explicitly passing the backend URL. I also configured CORS in Express to permit WebSocket upgrade requests from external origins."*

---

### Concept 14: Internal DNS Hijacking in Node.js

**The Problem:** Mongoose hung indefinitely connecting to MongoDB Atlas with `querySrv ECONNREFUSED`. The OS-level `nslookup` command worked fine — it was Node.js-specific.

**The Root Cause:** Node.js uses an internal C++ DNS library called **`c-ares`** for DNS resolution. On restricted networks (VPNs, corporate firewalls, certain ISP filters), `c-ares` gets blocked from querying `SRV` DNS records — which MongoDB Atlas connection strings use for cluster discovery.

**The Fix:**
```js
// config/db.js — Override Node's DNS resolver before connecting
import dns from "dns"
dns.setServers(["8.8.8.8", "8.8.4.4"]) // Force Google's public DNS

export const connectDB = async () => {
  await mongoose.connect(process.env.MONGO_URI)
}
```

> **Interview Q:** *"What was the most difficult infrastructure bug you resolved?"*
>
> **Your Answer:** *"The hardest was a Node.js-specific DNS failure connecting to MongoDB Atlas. The OS could resolve the hostname fine, but Node's internal `c-ares` resolver was being blocked by the network from querying SRV DNS records — which MongoDB Atlas uses for cluster discovery. I diagnosed this by comparing `nslookup` output against Node's `dns.resolve()` output. The fix was importing the `dns` module and calling `dns.setServers(['8.8.8.8'])` before connecting — forcing Node to bypass the local DNS resolver and query Google's public DNS directly."*

---

## 🟢 PHASE 5: Authentication System (Clerk Integration)

### Concept 15: Third-Party Identity Providers (Clerk)

**The Problem:** Building custom auth (bcrypt password hashing, JWT generation/rotation, OAuth callbacks, refresh token management, session revocation) is a months-long project with significant security liability if any step is wrong.

**The Solution:** **Clerk** as an Identity Provider (IdP).

```jsx
// main.jsx — Wrap the app in Clerk's provider
<ClerkProvider publishableKey={import.meta.env.VITE_CLERK_PUBLISHABLE_KEY}>
  <App />
</ClerkProvider>

// Anywhere in the app
const { user, isLoaded } = useUser()
const clerkUserId = user?.id  // e.g., "user_2abc123xyz"
```

**What Clerk handles for you:** OAuth providers (Google, GitHub), session management, JWTs, CSRF protection, MFA, email verification, and passwordless login.

> **Interview Q:** *"Why did you use Clerk instead of building auth from scratch?"*
>
> **Your Answer:** *"I understand JWT-based auth with bcrypt and Passport.js, but I chose Clerk to eliminate the security liability. A single mistake in token rotation, CSRF protection, or OAuth callback handling can be catastrophic. Clerk is an enterprise-grade Identity Provider that handles all of that, audited by security professionals. It let me focus on the collaborative features — the actual differentiator of the product — rather than reinventing a solved problem."*

---

### Concept 16: Relational Workspaces (User Dashboards)

**The Problem:** Without auth, anyone with a link can join anonymously and users can't track their history.

**The Solution:** Tying MongoDB `Workspace` documents to Clerk user IDs.

```js
// Workspace.model.js
const WorkspaceSchema = new mongoose.Schema({
  roomId:    { type: String, required: true, unique: true },
  ownerId:   { type: String, required: true }, // Clerk user.id
  name:      { type: String, required: true },
  content:   { type: String, default: "" },
  createdAt: { type: Date, default: Date.now },
})
```

```js
// workspace.controller.js — Dashboard query
export const getUserWorkspaces = async (req, res) => {
  const { ownerId } = req.query
  const workspaces = await Workspace.find({ ownerId }).sort({ createdAt: -1 })
  res.json({ success: true, workspaces })
}
```

> **Interview Q:** *"How does your application map users to their content?"*
>
> **Your Answer:** *"I used a relational pattern in MongoDB. The Workspace schema stores an `ownerId` field set to the user's unique Clerk ID. When an authenticated user creates a workspace, the frontend extracts `user.id` from Clerk and sends it in the POST body. The dashboard query is a simple `Workspace.find({ ownerId })`. This transforms the app from a stateless session tool into a persistent, personalized SaaS platform."*

---

## 🟢 PHASE 6: AI Intent Mode (Gemini API Integration)

### Concept 17: Service Layer for External AI APIs (Gemini)

**The Problem:** The Gemini API key must never be exposed in the frontend JavaScript bundle — any user could open DevTools and extract it. We also need a clean abstraction so the AI provider (Gemini, Claude, OpenAI) can be swapped without touching controllers or UI code.

**The Solution:** A `gemini.service.js` in the existing `services/` layer — mirroring the Judge0 pattern exactly. The Node.js server acts as a secure proxy.

```js
// server/src/services/gemini.service.js
import { GoogleGenerativeAI } from "@google/generative-ai";

const genAI = new GoogleGenerativeAI(process.env.GEMINI_API_KEY);

export const queryGemini = async (action, payload) => {
  const model = genAI.getGenerativeModel({ model: process.env.GEMINI_MODEL || "gemini-2.0-flash" });
  const fullPrompt = buildSystemPrompt(action, payload);
  const result = await model.generateContent(fullPrompt);
  return result.response.text();
};
```

**Architecture:**
```
[React Client — AiPanel.jsx]
     │
     │  POST /api/ai
     │  { action, code, language, prompt?, stderr? }
     ▼
[Express Server] ── ai.controller.js (validates input)
     │
     │  gemini.service.js (builds prompt, calls Gemini SDK)
     ▼
[Google Gemini API]  ← GEMINI_API_KEY stays server-side only
     │
     │  { candidates[0].content.parts[0].text }
     ▼
[Express Server] → { success: true, result: "<markdown>" }
     │
     ▼
[React Client — AiPanel renders response]
```

> **Interview Q:** *"How did you keep your AI API key secure in a React app?"*
>
> **Your Answer:** *"I never let the Gemini API key touch the frontend bundle. Instead, I built a server-side proxy using the same service layer pattern as my Judge0 integration — a `gemini.service.js` that the client never directly calls. The React client posts to `POST /api/ai` on my own Express server, which holds the key in a `.env` file and calls Gemini on the client's behalf. The key is never serialized into any JavaScript the browser downloads."*

---

### Concept 18: Prompt Engineering Architecture

**The Problem:** Four different AI features (Explain, Refactor, Generate, Debug) each need carefully-crafted prompts. Scattering prompt strings across controllers or components creates unmaintainable code.

**The Solution:** A single `buildSystemPrompt(action, payload)` function inside `gemini.service.js` — the sole source of truth for all prompt engineering.

```js
function buildSystemPrompt(action, { code, language, prompt, stderr }) {
  const lang = language || "plaintext";
  switch (action) {
    case "explain":  return `You are an expert ${lang} developer. Explain...\n\`\`\`${lang}\n${code}\n\`\`\``;
    case "refactor": return `Refactor for readability and performance...\n\`\`\`${lang}\n${code}\n\`\`\``;
    case "generate": return `Generate clean ${lang} code for: ${prompt}`;
    case "debug":    return `Diagnose this error...\nCode:\n${code}\nError:\n${stderr}`;
  }
}
```

> **Interview Q:** *"How did you structure your AI prompts?"*
>
> **Your Answer:** *"I centralized all prompt engineering in a single `buildSystemPrompt()` function inside the service layer. It takes an action type and a payload, and returns the complete, context-aware prompt string. This means improving any prompt — say, adding chain-of-thought instructions to the debug prompt — only touches one function and is immediately testable in isolation."*

---

### Concept 19: CRDT Safety with AI Suggestions

**The Problem:** In a collaborative editor, if AI suggestions were automatically inserted into the shared document, every collaborator would see an unsolicited AI edit appear in their editor mid-session. This could disrupt other users' work and violates the principle that all document changes should be intentional user actions.

**The Solution:** AI responses are **never written back to the Yjs CRDT automatically**. The panel renders the AI response as read-only text. The user must manually copy and paste any suggestion into the editor — at which point it becomes a normal Yjs operation, attributed to that user, and synced to all peers through the CRDT.

```
✅ AI Response  →  AiPanel (read-only <pre>)  →  User manually pastes  →  Monaco  →  Yjs CRDT  →  All peers
❌ AI Response  →  ydoc.getText("monaco").insert(...)  ← This would bypass user intent and attribution
```

> **Interview Q:** *"How does AI interact with your real-time collaborative CRDT system?"*
>
> **Your Answer:** *"Intentionally, AI responses don't interact with Yjs at all. The AI panel renders its suggestions as read-only text outside the editor. If a user wants to apply a suggestion, they manually paste it — at that point it becomes a normal, attributed CRDT operation that syncs to all peers like any other keystroke. Auto-inserting AI content would break collaborative trust: a collaborator might see code appear in their editor with no obvious author. The manual apply step preserves intentionality and attribution."*

---

### Concept 20: Context-Aware AI via Monaco Selection API

**The Problem:** Sending the entire file to Gemini for a question about a single function wastes tokens, increases latency, and produces less focused responses.

**The Solution:** The `AiPanel` reads the Monaco editor's current selection via `editorRef.current.getSelection()`. If the user has selected a region, only that region is sent. If nothing is selected, the full file is sent.

```js
// AiPanel.jsx — getCode()
const getCode = () => {
  const selection = editorRef.current.getSelection();
  const model = editorRef.current.getModel();
  if (selection && !selection.isEmpty()) {
    return model.getValueInRange(selection);   // Only the selection
  }
  return editorRef.current.getValue();         // Full file fallback
}
```

> **Interview Q:** *"How does the AI know what code the user is asking about?"*
>
> **Your Answer:** *"I used Monaco's `getSelection()` API to check if the user has highlighted a specific region of code. If they have, I send only that range via `getValueInRange()`. If nothing is selected, I fall back to the full editor content. This makes the AI context-aware without requiring any special UI — the user just highlights a function and clicks Explain, exactly like they would in any modern IDE."*

---

### Concept 21: Architectural Consistency (The Service Layer Pattern)

The AI integration added **0 new architectural patterns**. Every decision mirrors the existing Judge0 integration:

| Concern | Judge0 (Code Execution) | Gemini (AI Intent) |
|---|---|---|
| **Service file** | `judge0.service.js` | `gemini.service.js` |
| **Controller** | `execution.controller.js` | `ai.controller.js` |
| **Route** | `execution.routes.js` | `ai.routes.js` |
| **Endpoint** | `POST /api/execution/run` | `POST /api/ai` |
| **Key discriminator** | `languageId` in body | `action` in body |
| **Frontend hook** | Inline in `Room.jsx` | `useAi.js` custom hook |
| **Key security** | None needed | `GEMINI_API_KEY` in `.env` |

> **Interview Q:** *"How did adding AI features change your backend architecture?"*
>
> **Your Answer:** *"It didn't change the architecture at all — that was the goal. The existing MVC + Service Layer pattern absorbed the new feature perfectly. I added one service, one controller, and one route file, each following the exact same structure as the Judge0 integration I'd already built. The `server.js` entry point needed only two new lines. The architectural investment in Phase 4 paid dividends in Phase 6."*



